    "brief": "CJC-1295 is a synthetic GHRH mimic that binds to pituitary receptors to trigger GH secretion, which then elevates insulin-like growth factor-1 (IGF-1) levels. Ipamorelin is a pentapeptide that acts as a ghrelin mimic, stimulating GH release by targeting ghrelin receptors without impacting prolactin or cortisol.",
    "description": "CJC-1295 is a long-acting GHRH analog that increases its half-life by binding to endogenous albumin. The \"no DAC\" version (also known as Modified GRF 1-29) consists of 29 amino acids from GHRH with four substitutions to improve receptor binding and stability, which may better replicate natural pulsatile growth hormone (GH) secretion.Ipamorelin is a synthetic pentapeptide (Aib-His-D-2-Nal-D-Phe-Lys-NH2) and a selective growth hormone secretagogue (GHS) that functions as a ghrelin mimetic to stimulate pituitary GH release. It is recognized for its high potency and its ability to release GH without significantly altering cortisol or ACTH levels.This blend potentially enhances GH release by concurrently targeting both GHRH and ghrelin receptors. It contains a 10mg total mixture, comprised of 5mg of CJC-1295 (No DAC) and 5mg of Ipamorelin.Properties of CJC 1295 & IpamorelinPeptide Sequence:CJC 1295: H-Tyr-D-Ala-Asp-Ala-Ile-Phe-Thr-Gln-Ser-Tyr-Arg-Lys-Val-Leu-Ala-Gln-Leu-Ser-Ala-Arg-Lys-Leu-Leu-Gln-Asp-Ile-Leu-Ser-Arg-NH2Ipamorelin: Aib-His-D-2-Nal-D-Phe-Lys-NH2Chemical Formula:CJC 1295: $C_{152}H_{252}N_{44}O_{42}$Ipamorelin: $C_{38}H_{49}N_{9}O_{5}$Molecular Mass:CJC 1295: 3,364.9 g/molIpamorelin: 711.9 g/molVial Size: 3ml This content is provided strictly for research purposes and does not constitute an endorsement or recommendation for the non-laboratory application or improper handling of peptides designed for research. The information, including discussions about specific peptides and their researched benefits, is presented for informational purposes only and must not be construed as health, clinical, or legal guidance, nor an encouragement for non-research use in humans. Peptides described here are solely for use in structured scientific study by authorized individuals. We advise consulting with research experts, medical practitioners, or legal counsel prior to any decisions about obtaining or utilizing these peptides. The expectation of responsible, ethical utilization of this information for legitimate investigative and scholarly objectives is paramount. This notice is dynamic and governs all provided content on research peptides.",
    "research": "Research\nBoth CJC-1295 and Ipamorelin are extensively investigated for their capacity to enhance growth hormone (GH) secretion.\n\nGrowth Hormone Release\nIn studies utilizing GHRH knockout mouse models, CJC-1295 effectively normalized both body length and weight, indicating significant potential for addressing growth-related deficiencies, with daily administration showing superior efficacy over less frequent intervals.¹ Clinical research in healthy adults has demonstrated that CJC-1295 induces a dose-dependent elevation in both GH and IGF-I concentrations, with sustained effects observed for up to 28 days. The peptide was well-tolerated in these trials, with no serious adverse effects documented.²\n\nIpamorelin acts as a selective GH secretagogue by mimicking ghrelin; it binds to the ghrelin receptor (GHSR) to trigger targeted GH release from the pituitary gland. Unlike other secretagogues, Ipamorelin does not induce significant elevations in cortisol or ACTH levels.³ Animal research indicates that Ipamorelin promotes longitudinal bone growth and body weight gain in a dose-dependent fashion. It appears to influence growth mechanisms directly, enhancing GH release without mirroring the effects on other growth factors like IGF-I.⁴ Furthermore, in vivo studies have confirmed that Ipamorelin exhibits dose-proportional pharmacokinetics, maintaining a short half-life while consistently stimulating GH release across a variety of tested doses.⁵\n\nReferences\nAlba, M., Fintini, D., Sagazio, A., Lawrence, B., Castaigne, J., Frohman, L., & Salvatori, R. (2006). Once-daily administration of CJC-1295, a long-acting growth hormone-releasing hormone (GHRH) analog, normalizes growth in the GHRH knockout mouse.. American journal of physiology. Endocrinology and metabolism, 291 6, E1290-4 . https://doi.org/10.1152/AJPENDO.00201.2006.\n\nTeichman, S., Neale, A., Lawrence, B., Gagnon, C., Castaigne, J., & Frohman, L. (2006). Prolonged stimulation of growth hormone (GH) and insulin-like growth factor I secretion by CJC-1295, a long-acting analog of GH-releasing hormone, in healthy adults.. The Journal of clinical endocrinology and metabolism, 91 3, 799-805 . https://doi.org/10.1210/JC.2005-1536.\n\nRaun, K., Hansen, B., Johansen, N., Thøgersen, H., Madsen, K., Ankersen, M., & Andersen, P. (1998). Ipamorelin, the first selective growth hormone secretagogue.. European journal of endocrinology, 139 5, 552-61 . https://doi.org/10.1530/EJE.0.1390552.\n\nJohansen, P., Nowak, J., Skjaerbaek, C., Flyvbjerg, A., Andreassen, T., Wilken, M., & Orskov, H. (1999). Ipamorelin, a new growth-hormone-releasing peptide, induces longitudinal bone growth in rats.. Growth hormone & IGF research : official journal of the Growth Hormone Research Society and the International IGF Research Society, 9 2, 106-13 . https://doi.org/10.1054/GHIR.1999.9998.\n\nGobburu, J., Agersø, H., Jusko, W., & Ynddal, L. (1999). Pharmacokinetic-Pharmacodynamic Modeling of Ipamorelin, a Growth Hormone Releasing Peptide, in Human Volunteers. Pharmaceutical Research, 16, 1412-1416. https://doi.org/10.1023/A:1018955126402.",
