    "brief": "Tesamorelin is a synthetic 44-amino acid analog of growth hormone-releasing hormone (GHRH). It acts as a potent stimulator of endogenous growth hormone secretion and is a significant compound for investigating the physiological mechanisms and regulatory functions of the growth hormone axis.",
    "description": "DescriptionTesamorelin is a synthetic peptide analog of GHRH, featuring a trans-3-hexenoic acid moiety at the N-terminus of its 44-amino acid sequence. This structural modification enhances its stability compared to endogenous GHRH. In laboratory settings, the compound stimulates the pituitary gland to secrete growth hormone, subsequently elevating levels of insulin-like growth factor-1 (IGF-1) and insulin-like growth factor binding protein-3 (IGFBP-3).Properties of TesamorelinPeptide Sequence: Tyr-Ala-Asp-Ala-Ile-Phe-Thr-Asn-Ser-Tyr-Arg-Lys-Val-Leu-Gly-Gln-Leu-Ser-Ala-Arg-Lys-Leu-Leu-Gln-Asp-Ile-Met-Ser-Arg-Gln-Gln-Gly-Glu-Ser-Asn-Gln-Glu-Arg-Gly-Ala-Arg-Ala-Arg-LeuChemical Formula: $C_{223}H_{370}N_{72}O_{69}S$Molecular Mass: 5,196 g/molCAS Number: 901758-09-6PubChem: 44147413Vial Size: 3mlLyophilized Peptides:These peptides undergo a freeze-drying process to preserve their purity and integrity while significantly extending their shelf life. No fillers are utilized during this manufacturing process.This content is provided strictly for research purposes and does not constitute an endorsement or recommendation for the non-laboratory application or improper handling of peptides designed for research. The information, including discussions about specific peptides and their researched benefits, is presented for informational purposes only and must not be construed as health, clinical, or legal guidance, nor an encouragement for non-research use in humans. Peptides described here are solely for use in structured scientific study by authorized individuals. We advise consulting with research experts, medical practitioners, or legal counsel prior to any decisions about obtaining or utilizing these peptides. The expectation of responsible, ethical utilization of this information for legitimate investigative and scholarly objectives is paramount. This notice is dynamic and governs all provided content on research peptides.",
    "research": "Research\nTesamorelin is a stabilized GHRH analog that modulates metabolism by influencing the growth hormone/IGF-1 axis. Research models indicate the compound can affect visceral adipose tissue, lipid profiles, and triglyceride levels through anabolic and lipolytic processes, typically without significantly altering glucose homeostasis in controlled research environments.\n\nEfficacy in Reducing Visceral Adipose Tissue\nStudies have demonstrated that Tesamorelin effectively decreases visceral adipose tissue (VAT) in individuals with HIV-associated lipodystrophy. Clinical analysis of two phase 3 trials indicated a significant reduction in VAT without substantial changes to subcutaneous adipose tissue; however, the VAT reduction was typically lost upon the discontinuation of the therapy.¹ Furthermore, Tesamorelin usage was associated with improvements in trunk fat, waist circumference, and overall body image parameters.¹\n\nImpact on Non-Alcoholic Fatty Liver Disease (NAFLD)\nTesamorelin has shown potential in mitigating liver fat and fibrosis progression in cases of HIV-associated NAFLD. Randomized placebo-controlled data suggests that the peptide reduces hepatic fat fraction and improves fibrosis-related gene expression.² Mechanistically, the peptide appears to modulate hepatic pathways by increasing oxidative phosphorylation while simultaneously downregulating inflammation-related gene expressions.²\n\nEffects on Fat Quality\nBeyond simple reduction in fat mass, research suggests Tesamorelin may improve the quality of remaining adipose tissue. Trials measuring fat density have shown an increase in both VAT and subcutaneous adipose tissue density, indicating that the peptide positively influences fat quality independently of changes in total fat quantity.³\n\nCardiovascular and Metabolic Outcomes\nInvestigations into cardiovascular disease (CVD) risk have suggested that Tesamorelin may contribute to a modest decrease in 10-year atherosclerotic CVD risk scores, a finding primarily linked to reductions in total cholesterol levels, even among patients currently using lipid-lowering therapies.⁴ Importantly, these metabolic benefits occurred without significant deviations in glucose parameters compared to placebo groups.¹\n\nNeurocognitive and Other Health Implications\nWhile the peptide effectively reduces waist circumference, trials investigating its impact on neurocognitive impairment in abdominally obese subjects with HIV found no significant difference compared to standard care.⁵ Nonetheless, the peptide’s capacity to elevate IGF-1 levels remains a focus for further experimental research applications.⁵\n\nReferences\nFalutz, J., Mamputu, J., Potvin, D., Moyle, G., Soulban, G., Loughrey, H., Marsolais, C., Turner, R., & Grinspoon, S. (2010). Effects of tesamorelin (TH9507), a growth hormone-releasing factor analog, in human immunodeficiency virus-infected patients with excess abdominal fat: a pooled analysis of two multicenter, double-blind placebo-controlled phase 3 trials with safety extension data.. The Journal of clinical endocrinology and metabolism, 95 9, 4291-304 . https://doi.org/10.1210/jc.2010-0490.\n\nFourman, L., Billingsley, J., Agyapong, G., Sui, S., Feldpausch, M., Purdy, J., Zheng, I., Pan, C., Corey, K., Torriani, M., Kleiner, D., Hadigan, C., Stanley, T., Chung, R., & Grinspoon, S. (2020). Effects of tesamorelin on hepatic transcriptomic signatures in HIV-associated NAFLD. JCI Insight, 5. https://doi.org/10.1172/jci.insight.140134.\n\nLake, J., La, K., Erlandson, K., Adrian, S., Yenokyan, G., Scherzinger, A., Dubé, M., Stanley, T., Grinspoon, S., Falutz, J., Mamputu, J., Marsolais, C., McComsey, G., & Brown, T. (2021). Tesamorelin improves fat quality independent of changes in fat quantity. AIDS, 35, 1395 – 1402. https://doi.org/10.1097/QAD.0000000000002897.\n\nGrinspoon, S., Fourman, L., Stanley, T., McGary, C., Benkeser, D., & Cash, R. (2025). P-433. Impact of Tesamorelin on Cardiovascular Disease Risk Prediction Scores in Phase 3 Studies Treatment Arms: Subanalysis. Open Forum Infectious Diseases, 12. https://doi.org/10.1093/ofid/ofae631.633.\n\nEllis, R., Vaida, F., Hu, K., Dube, M., Henry, B., Chow, F., Heaton, R., Lee, D., & Sattler, F. (2025). Effects of Tesamorelin on Neurocognitive Impairment in Abdominally Obese Persons with HIV.. The Journal of infectious diseases. https://doi.org/10.1093/infdis/jiaf012.",
