    "brief": "TB-500 is a synthetic peptide based on the central actin-binding domain of the naturally occurring 43-amino-acid protein Thymosin Beta-4 (Tβ4). It is primarily utilized in in vitro and in vivo research to investigate its role in cellular motility, angiogenesis, and tissue repair through the modulation of actin dynamics.",
    "description": "DescriptionTB-500 is a synthetic version of the naturally occurring Thymosin Beta-4 peptide, which is found in most mammalian cell types. Tβ4 functions as a multifunctional regulatory molecule with distinct bioactive domains: the N-terminal tetrapeptide (Ac-SDKP) facilitates anti-inflammatory and antifibrotic actions, the N-terminal region (amino acids 1–15) promotes cell survival and prevents apoptosis, and the central actin-binding domain (amino acids 17–23, specifically the sequence LKKTET) is responsible for driving cell migration, wound healing, and angiogenesis.Properties of TB-500Peptide Sequence: Ac-Ser-Asp-Lys-Pro-Asp-Met-Ala-Glu-Ile-Glu-Lys-Phe-Asp-Lys-Ser-Lys-Leu-Lys-Lys-Thr-Glu-Thr-Gln-Glu-Lys-Asn-Pro-Leu-Pro-Ser-Lys-Glu-Thr-Ile-Glu-Gln-Glu-Lys-Gln-Ala-Gly-Glu-SerChemical Formula: $C_{212}H_{350}N_{56}O_{78}S$Molecular Mass: 4,963 g/molCAS Number: 77591-33-4PubChem: 16132341Vial Size: 3mlLyophilized Peptides:These peptides are provided in a freeze-dried, filler-free state to ensure stability, purity, and chemical integrity during storage. Reconstitute with sterile solvent immediately before experimental use.This content is provided strictly for research purposes and does not constitute an endorsement or recommendation for the non-laboratory application or improper handling of peptides designed for research. The information, including discussions about specific peptides and their researched benefits, is presented for informational purposes only and must not be construed as health, clinical, or legal guidance, nor an encouragement for non-research use in humans. Peptides described here are solely for use in structured scientific study by authorized individuals. We advise consulting with research experts, medical practitioners, or legal counsel prior to any decisions about obtaining or utilizing these peptides. The expectation of responsible, ethical utilization of this information for legitimate investigative and scholarly objectives is paramount. This notice is dynamic and governs all provided content on research peptides.",
    "research": "Research\nThymosin Beta-4 is a versatile peptide involved in a wide array of biological functions, including inflammation resolution, tissue regeneration, and stem cell modulation, making it a focus of diverse experimental applications.\n\nTissue Repair and Regeneration\nTβ4 is recognized for its ability to promote cell migration, blood vessel formation, and stem cell maturation.¹ It exhibits anti-inflammatory effects by downregulating pro-inflammatory chemokines and cytokines, while facilitating tissue repair through autophagy.² In the context of cardiac repair post-myocardial infarction, Tβ4 enhances cardiac function by stimulating resident epicardial progenitor cells and promoting neovascularization.³ Furthermore, its regenerative properties extend to the central nervous system, where it supports neurogenesis and protects against neurological injury by reducing apoptosis.⁴\n\nCardiovascular and Hepatic Applications\nResearch highlights the peptide's ability to improve the efficacy of stem cell therapies in ischemic conditions by enhancing cell migration and angiogenesis.⁵ Regarding hepatic health, Tβ4 has demonstrated potential in treating non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD) by inhibiting GPX4-mediated ferroptosis, thereby improving lipid metabolism and reducing oxidative stress within liver tissues.⁶\n\nOcular and Anti-Aging Research\nTβ4 is being investigated as an adjunct therapy for microbial keratitis, where it appears to reduce inflammation and accelerate corneal wound healing, potentially enhancing the efficacy of standard antibiotic treatments.⁷ Additionally, its capacity to reactivate embryonic regenerative programs suggests a future role in anti-aging therapies aimed at tissue and organ preservation.⁸\n\nReferences\nPhilp, D., & Kleinman, H. (2010). Animal studies with thymosin β4, a multifunctional tissue repair and regeneration peptide. Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences, 1194. https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1749-6632.2010.05479.x.\n\nRenga, G. et al. (2018). Thymosin β4 limits inflammation through autophagy. Expert Opinion on Biological Therapy, 18, 171–175. https://doi.org/10.1080/14712598.2018.1473854.\n\nBjorklund, G. et al. (2019). Thymosin β4: a multi-faceted tissue repair stimulating protein in heart injury. Current Medicinal Chemistry. https://doi.org/10.2174/0929867326666190716125456.\n\nZhang, G. et al. (2020). Protective effect of Tβ4 on central nervous system tissues and its developmental prospects. European Journal of Inflammation, 18. https://doi.org/10.1177/2058739220934559.\n\nKim, J. et al. (2020). Thymosin Beta4 Enhancing Therapeutic Efficacy of Human Adipose-derived Stem Cells in Mouse Ischemic Hindlimb Model. Circulation Research. https://doi.org/10.1161/res.127.suppl_1.469.\n\nZhu, Z. et al. (2021). Thymosin beta 4 alleviates non-alcoholic fatty liver by inhibiting ferroptosis via up-regulation of GPX4. European Journal of Pharmacology, 174351. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ejphar.2021.174351.\n\nSosne, G., & Berger, E. (2023). Thymosin beta 4: A potential novel adjunct treatment for bacterial keratitis. International Immunopharmacology, 118, 109953. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.intimp.2023.109953.\n\nBock-Marquette, I. et al. (2023). Thymosin beta-4 denotes new directions towards developing prosperous anti-aging regenerative therapies. International Immunopharmacology, 116, 109741. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.intimp.2023.109741.",
