    "brief": "The KLOW peptide blend is a specialized research-grade formulation containing GHK-Cu, BPC-157, TB-500, and KPV. It is designed for in vitro laboratory investigations into the synergy between extracellular matrix activation, cytoprotective signaling, actin-dependent cell motility, and immune-modulatory pathways during tissue repair and inflammatory modulation.",
    "description": "DescriptionThis 80 mg lyophilized blend integrates four distinct regenerative peptides (50 mg GHK-Cu, 10 mg BPC-157, 10 mg TB-500, and 10 mg KPV) into a single vial, enabling researchers to study complementary pathways for tissue regeneration and anti-inflammatory action.GHK-Cu is a copper-binding tripeptide that modulates gene expression, stimulates collagen production, and drives angiogenesis. BPC-157 facilitates soft-tissue repair and cytoprotection through nitric-oxide signaling and cytokine balance. TB-500 enhances cell migration and angiogenesis via actin-sequestering pathways, while KPV is an anti-inflammatory tripeptide that modulates immune signaling and regulates mast cell activation. By investigating these peptides together, researchers can observe the potential synergy across copper-mediated matrix activation (GHK-Cu), cytoprotective signaling (BPC-157), actin-dependent cell motility (TB-500), and immune-modulatory pathways (KPV).Properties of KLOW Blend ComponentsGHK-Cu: $C_{14}H_{23}CuN_{6}O_{4}$ | Mass: 401.91 g/molBPC-157: $C_{62}H_{98}N_{16}O_{22}$ | Mass: 1,419.5 g/molTB-500: $C_{212}H_{350}N_{56}O_{78}S$ | Mass: 4,963.55 g/molKPV: $C_{17}H_{32}N_{6}O_{4}$ | Mass: 384.48 g/molVial Size: 3mlLyophilized Peptides:These peptides are supplied in a freeze-dried, filler-free state to maximize stability and preserve chemical integrity during storage. Reconstitute with sterile solvent immediately prior to experimental use and store aliquots at ≤ –20 °C to prevent repeated freeze–thaw cycles.This content is provided strictly for research purposes and does not constitute an endorsement or recommendation for the non-laboratory application or improper handling of peptides designed for research. The information, including discussions about specific peptides and their researched benefits, is presented for informational purposes only and must not be construed as health, clinical, or legal guidance, nor an encouragement for non-research use in humans. Peptides described here are solely for use in structured scientific study by authorized individuals. We advise consulting with research experts, medical practitioners, or legal counsel prior to any decisions about obtaining or utilizing these peptides. The expectation of responsible, ethical utilization of this information for legitimate investigative and scholarly objectives is paramount. This notice is dynamic and governs all provided content on research peptides.",
    "research": "Research\nLaboratory investigations of the KLOW peptide combination reveal synergistic mechanisms for cellular repair, vascular formation, and inflammatory modulation, providing valuable tools for in vitro research applications.\n\nAngiogenesis and Vascular Formation\nBPC-157 upregulates VEGFR2 expression to activate the VEGFR2-Akt-eNOS signaling cascade.¹ GHK-Cu increases VEGF and bFGF expression,² and TB-500 functions as a chemoattractant, stimulating significant HUVEC migration.³\n\nTissue Repair and Regeneration\nGHK-Cu modulates thousands of genes to facilitate matrix remodeling via integrin-linked kinase.⁴ BPC-157 promotes regeneration through FAK-paxillin pathway activation,⁵ and TB-500 increases reepithelialization and collagen deposition through its role in G-actin sequestration.⁶\n\nCollagen Synthesis and Extracellular Matrix\nGHK-Cu stimulates collagen synthesis and decorin production at nanomolar concentrations.⁷ BPC-157 enhances collagen and reticulin formation across various tissues,⁸ and TB-500 promotes the deposition of tightly organized mature collagen fibers.⁹\n\nInflammatory Modulation and Oxidative Stress\nKPV inhibits NF-κB activation by stabilizing IκB-α and preventing p65RelA nuclear translocation.¹⁰ GHK-Cu and BPC-157 further suppress pro-inflammatory cytokines like TNF-α and IL-6 while quenching ROS and upregulating antioxidant enzymes such as superoxide dismutase.¹¹,¹² Additionally, KPV reduces fine-dust-induced apoptosis and inflammation by modulating MAPK/NF-κB signaling pathways.¹³\n\nReferences\nHsieh, M.-J. et al. (2016). Therapeutic potential of pro-angiogenic BPC157 is associated with VEGFR2 activation and up-regulation. https://doi.org/10.1007/s00109-016-1488-y\n\nDou, Y. et al. (2020). The potential of GHK as an anti-aging peptide. https://doi.org/10.31491/apt.2020.03.014\n\nMalinda, K. M. et al. (1997). Thymosin β 4 stimulates directional migration of human umbilical vein endothelial cells. https://doi.org/10.1096/fasebj.11.6.9194528\n\nPickart, L. & Margolina, A. (2018). Regenerative and Protective Actions of the GHK-Cu Peptide in the Light of the New Gene Data. https://doi.org/10.3390/ijms19071987\n\nChang, C.-H. et al. (2011). The promoting effect of pentadecapeptide BPC 157 on tendon healing involves tendon outgrowth, cell survival, and cell migration. https://doi.org/10.1152/japplphysiol.00945.2010\n\nXue, B. et al. (2014). Structural basis of thymosin-β4/profilin exchange leading to actin filament polymerization. https://doi.org/10.1073/pnas.1412271111\n\nMaquart, F.-X. et al. (1988). Stimulation of collagen synthesis in fibroblast cultures by the tripeptide‐copper complex glycyl‐L‐histidyl‐L‐lysine‐Cu2+. https://doi.org/10.1016/0014-5793(88)80509-x\n\nSeiwerth, S. et al. (2021). Stable Gastric Pentadecapeptide BPC 157 and Wound Healing. https://doi.org/10.3389/fphar.2021.627533\n\nMalinda, K. M. et al. (1999). Thymosin beta4 accelerates wound healing.\n\nDalmasso, G. et al. (2008). PepT1-Mediated Tripeptide KPV Uptake Reduces Intestinal Inflammation. https://doi.org/10.1053/j.gastro.2007.10.026\n\nDemirtaş, H. et al. (2025). Protective Effects of BPC 157 on Liver, Kidney, and Lung Distant Organ Damage. https://doi.org/10.3390/medicina61020291\n\nSharma, S. et al. (2019). In Vitro and in Vivo Studies of pH-Sensitive GHK-Cu-Incorporated Polyaspartic and Polyacrylic Acid Superabsorbent Polymer. https://doi.org/10.1021/acsomega.9b00655\n\nSung, J. et al. (2025). Lysine-Proline-Valine peptide mitigates fine dust-induced keratinocyte apoptosis and inflammation by regulating oxidative stress and modulating the MAPK/NF-κB pathway. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.tice.2025.102837",
