    "brief": "Epitalon is a synthetic tetrapeptide derivative of the natural pineal gland extract epithalamin, composed of the amino acids alanine, glutamic acid, aspartic acid, and glycine. It is primarily investigated in laboratory settings for its potential geroprotective properties, including the modulation of telomere dynamics and telomerase activity.",
    "description": "DescriptionEpitalon (Ala-Glu-Asp-Gly) was developed at the St. Petersburg Institute of Bioregulation and Gerontology as a synthetic mimic of epithalamin. Within longevity and bioregulation research, Epitalon is studied for its capacity to influence cellular aging pathways. It has garnered significant attention for its ability to modulate telomerase—the enzyme responsible for rebuilding telomeres—which are the protective sequences at the ends of chromosomes that typically shorten during cellular division.Properties of EpitalonPeptide Sequence: Ala-Glu-Asp-GlyChemical Formula: $C_{14}H_{22}N_{4}O_{9}$Molecular Mass: 390.35 g/molCAS Number: 307297-39-8PubChem: 219042Vial Size: 3mlThis content is provided strictly for research purposes and does not constitute an endorsement or recommendation for the non-laboratory application or improper handling of peptides designed for research. The information, including discussions about specific peptides and their researched benefits, is presented for informational purposes only and must not be construed as health, clinical, or legal guidance, nor an encouragement for non-research use in humans. Peptides described here are solely for use in structured scientific study by authorized individuals. We advise consulting with research experts, medical practitioners, or legal counsel prior to any decisions about obtaining or utilizing these peptides. The expectation of responsible, ethical utilization of this information for legitimate investigative and scholarly objectives is paramount. This notice is dynamic and governs all provided content on research peptides.",
    "research": "Research\nEpitalon is widely researched for its potential to alter aging-related physiological markers, with studies highlighting its impact on telomere length, oxidative stress, and tumorigenesis.\n\nTelomere Dynamics and Cellular Senescence\nResearch demonstrates that Epitalon activates telomerase in various cell types, inducing the expression of the telomerase catalytic subunit and facilitating telomere elongation.¹ By slowing telomere attrition, the peptide allows somatic cells to exceed the Hayflick limit—the standard threshold for cellular division—effectively delaying senescence and extending the proliferative potential of cells.²,⁵\n\nLongevity and Geroprotective Effects\nIn various animal models, including mice and Drosophila melanogaster, Epitalon has been linked to increased lifespan, with some studies reporting extensions in both average and maximum survival.³⁻⁵ Its geroprotective effects are further supported by its ability to reduce chromosomal aberrations, suggesting an antimutagenic mechanism, and its capacity to restore age-related hormonal imbalances, such as melatonin and glucose regulation, in primate models.⁶,⁷\n\nAntioxidant and Antitumor Activities\nEpitalon mitigates oxidative stress by lowering intracellular reactive oxygen species (ROS) levels and enhancing mitochondrial function, sometimes outperforming melatonin in direct antioxidant capacity.⁸ Additionally, the peptide has shown inhibitory effects on tumor growth in transgenic and chemical-induced carcinogenesis models.⁹,¹⁰ These antitumor properties are linked to the downregulation of specific oncogenes, such as HER-2/neu, and the modulation of gene expression patterns relevant to stress response and tissue health.¹¹,¹²\n\nReferences\nKhavinson, V. et al. (2003). Epithalon Peptide Induces Telomerase Activity and Telomere Elongation in Human Somatic Cells. Bulletin of Experimental Biology and Medicine, 135, 590–592. https://doi.org/10.1023/A:1025493705728.\n\nShi-Liang, T. (2007). Retarding the cellular senescence by Epithalon and changes of telomere length and telomerase activity in the retarding process. Journal of Chongqing College of Education.\n\nAnisimov, V. et al. (2004). Effect of Epitalon on biomarkers of aging, life span and spontaneous tumor incidence in female Swiss-derived SHR mice. Biogerontology, 4, 193–202. https://doi.org/10.1023/A:1025114230714.\n\nKhavinson, V. et al. (2000). Effect of epitalon on the lifespan increase in Drosophila melanogaster. Mechanisms of Ageing and Development, 120, 141–149. https://doi.org/10.1016/S0047-6374(00)00217-7.\n\nKhavinson, V. et al. (2004). Peptide Promotes Overcoming of the Division Limit in Human Somatic Cell. Bulletin of Experimental Biology and Medicine, 137, 503–506. https://doi.org/10.1023/B:BEBM.0000038164.49947.8c.\n\nRosenfeld, S. et al. (2002). Effect of Epithalon on the Incidence of Chromosome Aberrations in Senescence-Accelerated Mice. Bulletin of Experimental Biology and Medicine, 133, 274–276. https://doi.org/10.1023/A:1015899003974.\n\nGoncharova, N. et al. (2005). Pineal peptides restore the age-related disturbances in hormonal functions of the pineal gland and the pancreas. Experimental Gerontology, 40, 51–57. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.exger.2004.10.004.\n\nKozina, L. et al. (2007). Antioxidant properties of geroprotective peptides of the pineal gland. Archives of Gerontology and Geriatrics, 44, 213–216. https://doi.org/10.1016/J.ARCHGER.2007.01.029.\n\nAnisimov, V. et al. (2002). Epithalon Inhibits Tumor Growth and Expression of HER-2/neu Oncogene in Breast Tumors in Transgenic Mice. Bulletin of Experimental Biology and Medicine, 133, 167–170. https://doi.org/10.1023/A:1015555023692.\n\nAnisimov, V. et al. (2002). Inhibitory effect of peptide Epitalon on colon carcinogenesis induced by 1,2-dimethylhydrazine in rats. Cancer Letters, 183(1), 1–8. https://doi.org/10.1016/S0304-3835(02)00090-3.\n\nYue, X. et al. (2022). Epitalon protects against post-ovulatory aging-related damage of mouse oocytes in vitro. Aging, 14, 3191–3202. https://doi.org/10.18632/aging.204007.\n\nKhavinson, V., & Malinin, V. (2005). Gerontological Aspects of Genome Peptide Regulation. https://doi.org/10.1159/isbn.978-3-318-01193-7.",
