    "brief": "Melanotan-1 (afamelanotide) is a synthetic analog of the peptide hormone alpha-melanocyte-stimulating hormone ($\\alpha$-MSH). It serves as a selective agonist for melanocortin receptors, particularly MC1R, and is primarily utilized in laboratory research to investigate the mechanisms of melanogenesis, DNA repair, and anti-inflammatory signaling.",
    "description": "DescriptionMelanotan-1, also referred to as afamelanotide or melanotan-I, is a synthetic peptide hormone analog. Its primary activity involves binding to and activating melanocortin receptors, with a high affinity for the melanocortin-1 receptor (MC1R). By engaging this receptor, Melanotan-1 stimulates the cyclic AMP (cAMP) signaling cascade, which drives melanogenesis pathways in melanocyte cell cultures and facilitates melanin synthesis without the necessity of UV radiation. This compound is extensively used in research settings to study the biology of pigmentation, cellular signaling, and photoprotective mechanisms in dermal cell models.Properties of Melanotan-1Peptide Sequence: Ser-Tyr-Ser-Nle-Glu-His-D-Phe-Arg-Trp-Gly-Lys-Pro-ValChemical Formula: $C_{78}H_{111}N_{21}O_{19}$Molecular Mass: 1646.8 g/molCAS Number: 75921-69-6PubChem: 16154396Vial Size: 3mlLyophilized Peptides:These peptides are provided in a freeze-dried, filler-free state to maximize stability and preserve chemical integrity during storage. Reconstitute with sterile solvent immediately prior to experimental use.This content is provided strictly for research purposes and does not constitute an endorsement or recommendation for the non-laboratory application or improper handling of peptides designed for research. The information, including discussions about specific peptides and their researched benefits, is presented for informational purposes only and must not be construed as health, clinical, or legal guidance, nor an encouragement for non-research use in humans. Peptides described here are solely for use in structured scientific study by authorized individuals. We advise consulting with research experts, medical practitioners, or legal counsel prior to any decisions about obtaining or utilizing these peptides. The expectation of responsible, ethical utilization of this information for legitimate investigative and scholarly objectives is paramount. This notice is dynamic and governs all provided content on research peptides.",
    "research": "ResearchMelanotan-1 functions as a stable $\\alpha$-MSH analog, interacting with melanocortin receptors to influence diverse physiological processes, including pigment synthesis, DNA repair, and immune regulation.Melanogenesis and DNA RepairBinding to MC1R activates cAMP-dependent cascades that upregulate tyrosinase, promoting eumelanin production over pheomelanin.¹,² Beyond pigmentation, this signaling pathway enhances nucleotide excision repair by increasing the recruitment of XPA proteins to sites of DNA damage, thereby accelerating the removal of UV-induced photolesions.³Anti-Inflammatory and Antioxidant PathwaysEngagement of melanocortin receptors on macrophages modulates the NF-κB signaling pathway, resulting in a reduction of pro-inflammatory cytokines and nitric oxide generation.⁴,⁵ Furthermore, the pathway activates PI3K/Akt/Nrf2 signaling, which increases the expression of antioxidant enzymes such as superoxide dismutase and catalase, providing protection against oxidative stress and mitochondrial dysfunction.⁶,⁷Hepatic and Erythropoietic InvestigationsResearch suggests that melanocortin signaling may reduce neutrophil infiltration in hepatic tissue during inflammatory states.⁸ Additionally, studies in erythropoietic protoporphyria models have explored the peptide's potential to modulate erythroblast survival and protoporphyrin accumulation, highlighting its diverse therapeutic potential in clinical laboratory research.⁹References\nA. Polańska et al., “Afamelanotide in protoporphyria and other skin diseases: a review,” Termedia Sp. z.o.o., 2024. doi: 10.5114/ada.2024.138818.\n\nF. Wang, W. Ma, D. Fan, J. Hu, X. An, and Z. Wang, “The biochemistry of melanogenesis: an insight into the function and mechanism of melanogenesis-related proteins,” Frontiers Media SA, Aug. 2024. doi: 10.3389/fmolb.2024.1440187.\n\nS. Ma et al., “Structural mechanism of calcium-mediated hormone recognition and Gβ interaction by the human melanocortin-1 receptor,” Springer Science and Business Media LLC, Aug. 2021. doi: 10.1038/s41422-021-00557-y.\n\nE. M. Wolf Horrell, M. C. Boulanger, and J. A. D’Orazio, “Melanocortin 1 Receptor: Structure, Function, and Regulation,” Frontiers Media SA, May 2016. doi: 10.3389/fgene.2016.00095.\n\nH. B. Patel, T. Montero-Melendez, K. V. Greco, and M. Perretti, “Melanocortin Receptors as Novel Effectors of Macrophage Responses in Inflammation,” Frontiers Media SA, 2011. doi: 10.3389/fimmu.2011.00041.\n\nX. Wu et al., “NDP-MSH binding melanocortin-1 receptor ameliorates neuroinflammation and BBB disruption through CREB/Nr4a1/NF-κB pathway after intracerebral hemorrhage in mice,” Springer Science and Business Media LLC, Oct. 2019. doi: 10.1186/s12974-019-1591-4.\n\nW. Xu et al., “Activation of Melanocortin 1 Receptor Attenuates Early Brain Injury in a Rat Model of Subarachnoid Hemorrhage viathe Suppression of Neuroinflammation through AMPK/TBK1/NF-κB Pathway in Rats,” Elsevier BV, Jan. 2020. doi: 10.1007/s13311-019-00772-x.\n\nW. Xu et al., “Melanocortin 1 receptor attenuates early brain injury following subarachnoid hemorrhage by controlling mitochondrial metabolism via AMPK/SIRT1/PGC-1α pathway in rats,” Ivyspring International Publisher, 2021. doi: 10.7150/thno.49426.\n\nS. Fu et al., “Activation of the Melanocortin-1 Receptor by NDP-MSH Attenuates Oxidative Stress and Neuronal Apoptosis through PI3K/Akt/Nrf2 Pathway after Intracerebral Hemorrhage in Mice,” Wiley, Nov. 2020. doi: 10.1155/2020/8864100.\n\nS. Yu et al., “Activation of MC1R with BMS-470539 attenuates neuroinflammation via cAMP/PKA/Nurr1 pathway after neonatal hypoxic-ischemic brain injury in rats,” Springer Science and Business Media LLC, Jan. 2021. doi: 10.1186/s12974-021-02078-2.\n\nA.-E. Minder et al., “Beyond pigmentation: signs of liver protection during afamelanotide treatment in Swiss patients with erythropoietic protoporphyria, an observational study,” SAGE Publications, Jan. 2021. doi: 10.1177/26330040211065453.\n\nH. Chiao, S. Foster, R. Thomas, J. Lipton, and R. A. Star, “Alpha-melanocyte-stimulating hormone reduces endotoxin-induced liver inflammation.,” American Society for Clinical Investigation, May 1996. doi: 10.1172/jci118639.\n\nJ. G. Langendonk et al., “Afamelanotide for Erythropoietic Protoporphyria,” Massachusetts Medical Society, Jul. 2015. doi: 10.1056/nejmoa1411481.",
