    "brief": "5-Amino-1-methylquinolinium (5-Amino-1MQ) is a selective, small-molecule inhibitor of the enzyme nicotinamide N-methyltransferase (NNMT). It is utilized in laboratory research to investigate the modulation of cellular NAD+ levels, energy metabolism, and epigenetic pathways, with particular interest in its effects on adipocyte function and tumor microenvironments.",
    "description": "Description5-Amino-1MQ is a methylquinolinium derivative recognized for its potent inhibition of NNMT. By blocking this enzyme, the compound influences the methylation of nicotinamide, which subsequently modulates intracellular NAD+ pools and SAM levels. These changes have significant downstream effects on energy production, fat metabolism, and gene expression through histone methylation. It serves as a primary tool for researchers exploring metabolic disease models, mitochondrial function, and cancer-associated cellular pathways.Properties of 5-Amino-1MQChemical Formula: $C_{10}H_{11}N_{2}^{+}$ (as a quinolinium derivative)Molecular Mass: 159.21 g/molPubChem: 950107Vial Size: 3mlLyophilized Form:This compound is provided in a freeze-dried state to ensure stability and preserve chemical integrity. It is intended for reconstitution with sterile solvent immediately prior to experimental use.This content is provided strictly for research purposes and does not constitute an endorsement or recommendation for the non-laboratory application or improper handling of peptides or compounds designed for research. The information, including discussions about specific research compounds and their explored benefits, is presented for informational purposes only and must not be construed as health, clinical, or legal guidance, nor an encouragement for non-research use in humans. Compounds described here are solely for use in structured scientific study by authorized individuals. We advise consulting with research experts, medical practitioners, or legal counsel prior to any decisions about obtaining or utilizing these compounds. The expectation of responsible, ethical utilization of this information for legitimate investigative and scholarly objectives is paramount. This notice is dynamic and governs all provided content on research compounds.",
    "research": "Research\n\n5-Amino-1MQ is a focal point in metabolic and oncological studies, where it is used to examine how NNMT inhibition affects cellular energetics, obesity-related pathophysiology, and tumor growth.\n\nMetabolic and Anti-Obesity Research\n\nNNMT inhibition by 5-Amino-1MQ increases intracellular NAD+ levels, which is vital for redox balance and metabolic homeostasis.¹ In diet-induced obesity models, the compound has been shown to reduce body weight and white adipose tissue mass without affecting caloric intake, suggesting a mechanism that targets lipogenesis directly rather than appetite suppression.²,³\n\nOncological Applications\n\nIn cancer research, 5-Amino-1MQ is studied for its ability to modulate the tumor microenvironment, particularly within cancer-associated fibroblasts (CAFs). By altering histone methylation and cellular energetics, the compound inhibits tumor-supportive metabolic functions and reduces tumor cell proliferation, making it a candidate for studies involving combination therapeutic strategies.⁴,⁵\n\nMechanistic Pathways\n\nThe compound's activity bridges the gap between metabolic regulation and epigenetic remodeling. By preventing the consumption of S-adenosylmethionine (SAM) by NNMT, 5-Amino-1MQ preserves SAM availability for other methylation reactions, including those affecting histones, which regulates gene expression programs central to both healthy metabolism and oncogenesis.²,⁴ References\n\nConlon, N., & Ford, D. (2022). A systems-approach to NAD+ restoration.. Biochemical pharmacology, 114946 . https://doi.org/10.1016/j.bcp.2022.114946.\n\nMyong, S., Nguyen, A., & Challa, S. (2024). Biological Functions and Therapeutic Potential of NAD+ Metabolism in Gynecological Cancers. Cancers, 16. https://doi.org/10.3390/cancers16173085.\n\nLi, X., Pi, Y., Chen, Y., Zhu, Q., & Xia, B. (2022). Nicotinamide N-Methyltransferase: A Promising Biomarker and Target for Human Cancer Therapy. Frontiers in Oncology, 12. https://doi.org/10.3389/fonc.2022.894744.\n\nLiu, J., Deng, Z., Zhu, X., Zeng, Y., Guan, X., & Li, J. (2021). Roles of Nicotinamide N-Methyltransferase in Obesity and Type 2 Diabetes. BioMed Research International, 2021. https://doi.org/10.1155/2021/9924314.",
